Ringgit Drops on Speculation Borrowing Costs to Stay Unchanged

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-03-07T08:53:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/ringgit-drops-on-speculation-borrowing-costs-to-stay-unchanged.html
The ringgit weakened from near a 13-
year high on speculation the central bank will leave borrowing
costs unchanged this week to support growth as higher  oil prices 
threaten to stoke inflation.    Bank Negara Malaysia  will keep its overnight rate at 2.75
percent when it meets on March 11, according to six out of eight
economists in a Bloomberg News survey. Four predicted an
increase to 3 percent. The currency snapped a two-day rally
after oil extended a three-week rally to trade above $105 a
barrel, pressuring the government’s  budget deficit .  Government
bonds  slid.  “People are more concerned that higher oil prices will
affect subsidy bills and affect growth,” said Suresh Kumar Ramanathan, a currency strategist at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd.
in Kuala Lumpur. “It looks more likely that policy makers will
try to keep rates on hold to support a recovery.”  The ringgit fell 0.2 percent to 3.0310 per dollar as of
4:25 p.m. in  Kuala Lumpur , according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. It touched 3.0240 on Feb. 21, the strongest level
since October 1997.  Consumer prices rose 2.4 percent in January from a year
earlier, the fastest pace since May 2009, according to official
data. The government raised fuel and sugar prices twice in 2010
to help claw back some of its 73 billion ringgit ($24 billion)
in annual subsidies.  Prime Minister Najib Razak aims to narrow the budget
deficit to 2.8 percent of gross domestic product by 2015, from
an estimated 5.6 percent in 2010, according to the finance
ministry’s forecasts last year.  Bonds Fall  Five-year bonds dropped for a third day as traders sold
ahead of a scheduled debt auction. Yields jumped to the highest
level in a month.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015
increased 5 basis points, or 0.05 percentage point, to 3.5
percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The price dropped 0.2 or 2
ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face amount, to 101.35.  The government will offer more of existing notes maturing
in September 2016 later this month in the first of two auctions,
according to its sale calendar. It may disclose the date and
amount as early as tomorrow.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
